<p>HUMAN RIGHTS COUNCIL 
Ninth session 
Agenda item 3 
</p>
<p><b>PROMOTION AND PROTECTION OF ALL HUMAN RIGHTS, CIVIL,  
POLITICAL, ECONOMIC, SOCIAL AND CULTURAL RIGHTS,  
                INCLUDING THE RIGHT TO DEVELOPMENT 
</b></p>
<p><b>Estonia</b>*<b>, Georgia</b>*<b>, Latvia</b>*<b>, Lithuania</b>*<b>, Monaco</b>*<b>, Poland</b>*<b>,  
Republic of Moldova</b>*<b> and Ukraine: draft resolution 
</b></p>
<p><b>9/&#8230;  Remembrance of the <i>Holodomor</i> of 1932 and 1933 in Ukraine 
</b></p>
<p><i> The Human Rights Council, 
</i></p>
<p><i> Recalling </i>the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which reaffirms that the right to life 
is the first and essential human right, 
</p>
<p><i> Recalling also </i>the joint statement of 36 States Members of the United Nations on the 
seventieth anniversary of the <i>Holodomor </i>of 1932 and 1933 in Ukraine, circulated as a document 
of the fifty-eighth session of the United Nations General Assembly and in which the <i>Holodomor 
</i>was officially recognized as a national tragedy of the Ukrainian people, caused by the cruel 
actions and policies of the totalitarian Stalinist regime, 
</p>
<p>                                                 
</p>
<p>*  Non-member State of the Human Rights Council. </p>

 <p></p>
<p><i> Recalling further </i>the resolution of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural 
Organization on the remembrance of the victims of the <i>Holodomor </i>of 1932 and 1933 in Ukraine, 
adopted on 1 November 2007, and the joint statement on the seventy-fifth anniversary of the 
<i>Holodomor </i>of 1932 and 1933 in Ukraine, declared on 30 November 2007 by 32 States members 
of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, 
</p>
<p><i> Recalling</i> the resolution on the <i>Holodomor</i> of 1932 and 1933 in Ukraine, adopted 
on 3 July 2008 by the Parliamentary Assembly of the Organization for Security and Cooperation 
in Europe, 
</p>
<p> 1.<i> Expresses sympathy </i>to the victims of the <i>Holodomor </i>of 1932 and 1933 in Ukraine, 
an artificially created famine that took the lives of millions of Ukrainians, including 
representatives of other nationalities living in Ukraine at that time; 
</p>
<p> 2.<i> Welcomes </i>the initiative of Ukraine to organize commemorations on the occasion of 
the seventy-fifth anniversary of the <i>Holodomor </i>of 1932 and 1933 in Ukraine, and invites the 
member States of the Council to consider taking part in those events; 
</p>
<p> 3.<i> Stresses </i>the importance of raising public awareness of the <i>Holodomor </i>and of 
promoting respect for human life so that similar crimes will be prevented in the future; 
</p>
<p> 4. <i>Calls on </i>Member States to incorporate the knowledge on the <i>Holodomor</i> of 1932 
and 1933 in Ukraine in educational and research programmes to inculcate future generations 
with the lessons of this tragic page in history; 
</p>
<p> 5.<i> Emphasizes </i>that the memories of past horrors and crimes against humanity should 
lead the international community to redouble its efforts to ensure unconditional observance of 
the fundamental human rights of peoples and individuals throughout the world. 
</p>
